    {
        "content": "<p>Yep  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}/2\\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span><span class=\"mord\">/2</span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}/3\\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span><span class=\"mord\">/3</span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 562253910,
        "sender_full_name": "Tom",
        "timestamp": 1765041586
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"816344\">Aaron Liu</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/Stating.20the.20theorem.20that.20no.20ring.20isomorphism.20.202Z.20and.203Z/near/562253864\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>What is 2ℤ and 3ℤ?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><code>Ideal.span {2}</code> and <code>Ideal.span {3}</code></p>",
        "id": 562253943,
        "sender_full_name": "Snir Broshi",
        "timestamp": 1765041623
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>oh those aren't rings</p>",
        "id": 562253954,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1765041630
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>they're nonunital rings</p>",
        "id": 562253962,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1765041638
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah and they're both cyclic as additive groups so they are isomorphic</p>",
        "id": 562253980,
        "sender_full_name": "Snir Broshi",
        "timestamp": 1765041654
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>they're not isomorphic as nonunital rings</p>",
        "id": 562254028,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1765041706
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I flicked open dummit and foote which isnt the textbook I am working through to get more practice exercises and thats where I saw <code>2ℤ and 3ℤ</code>. I assumed this was different notation for  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}/2\\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span><span class=\"mord\">/2</span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}/3\\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span><span class=\"mord\">/3</span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span>. So I may have just confused myself by textbook hopping.</p>",
        "id": 562254032,
        "sender_full_name": "Tom",
        "timestamp": 1765041712
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think they're referring to the nonunital rings</p>",
        "id": 562254121,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1765041815
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>nℤ</code> is usually notation for the ideal in <code>ℤ</code> generated by <code>n</code>, and it's also the additive identity of <code>ℤ/nℤ</code>, where cosets are denoted by <code>nℤ+k</code></p>",
        "id": 562254130,
        "sender_full_name": "Snir Broshi",
        "timestamp": 1765041826
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I found the exercise</p>",
        "id": 562254170,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1765041881
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>Prove that the rings <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">2\\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">3\\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">3</span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span> are not isomorphic.</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 562254240,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1765041936
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>ℤ/nℤ</code> denotes residues mod <code>n</code> precisely because <code>nℤ</code> denotes the ideal, so taking a quotient by that ideal gives the residues</p>",
        "id": 562254243,
        "sender_full_name": "Snir Broshi",
        "timestamp": 1765041940
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ideals is the next chapter on the textbook I am actually working on :D</p>",
        "id": 562254294,
